<hl>
<seg id=1> Japanese PM hopes Miyazawa stay, continuing economic recovery program </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Tokyo, Reuters) Japanese Finance Minister Miyazawa Kiyichi encoutered pressure to stay in the cabinet. </seg>
<seg id=3> He annouced last week that he intended to resign soon. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Miyazawa's resignation also shadowed the coalition government made up by Prime Minister Obuchi Keizo's LDP and Ozawa Yichiro's Liberation Party. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> After senior officials' dispute over whether the cabinet post of the Liberation Party is part of the coalition agreement became aparent, the coalition government appeared instable. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> It is widely said that the general secretary of the Liberation Party Naeda will replace Miyazawa after his resignation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Miyazawa said last Friday that he possibly will resign from his position at the end of the year, but he did not give a date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> He told the news conference: "I can't say when." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is expected that he would still be the finance minister till the end of the two-week diet session of the congress. </seg>
<seg id=10> The congressional session will end on Dec. 14. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Deputy cabinet secretary of Obuchi Keizo, Suzuki told the Nihon Broadcasting Association Television that he believes that the PM want 79 year old Miyazawa to stay. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Suzuki said: "I think (Obuchi) privately want him to stay and continue to carry out his economic recovery program." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Obuchi is to talk with Miyazawa face to face. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said: "In consideration of his ability, it is not easy to find someone to replace him. </seg>
<seg id=15> I myself hope that he can stay and work for the rise of the economy of our country." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> Obuchi's comment on the possible resignation of Miyazawa to the outside is that he has read the sort of reports and he will talk to the finance minister. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
